[300,50],[300,100],[320,100]],&quot;desktop&quot;:[[728,90]],&quot;large_sc=
reen&quot;:[[728,90]]}" data-ad-glider-effect-mobile=3D"1" data-ad-wrapper-=
classes=3D""></div></div><p></p>
<p>We generally recommend buying 1-1/4 pounds of turkey per person. That ma=
y seem like a lot, but remember that this is the raw weight, which includes=
 excess water that evaporates during cooking and inedible weight (like the =
bones). You can use this easy formula: multiply the number of guests by 1.2=
5, then round up to the nearest whole number. So, if you=E2=80=99re expecti=
ng 12 guests, plan for a 15-pound bird.</p>
<p>Sometimes, it=E2=80=99s best to overestimate the amount of turkey people=
 will eat. Maybe you didn=E2=80=99t plan a lot of <a href=3D"https://www.ta=
steofhome.com/collection/favorite-thanksgiving-sides/" tabindex=3D"0" aria-=
label=3D"Thanksgiving sides" data-name=3D"Shop Now" data-module=3D"content =
engagement" data-position=3D"embedded links">Thanksgiving sides</a>, or may=
be you want to make sure there are leftovers. Feel free to increase the amo=
unt per person to 1-1/2 pounds. It is Thanksgiving, after all, so everyone =
will probably go back for seconds and take leftovers home.</p>
<p>If your guest count includes a lot of kids, simply round down when calcu=
lating how much turkey to make per person. The kids may not eat as much tur=
key and go for the rolls and&nbsp;sides&nbsp;instead, filling their stomach=
s with <a href=3D"https://www.tasteofhome.com/recipes/cream-cheese-mashed-p=
otatoes/" rel=3D"noopener" tabindex=3D"0" aria-label=3D"creamy mashed potat=
oes" data-name=3D"Shop Now" data-module=3D"content engagement" data-positio=
n=3D"embedded links">creamy mashed potatoes</a> and the cheese and crackers=
 from your <a href=3D"https://www.tasteofhome.com/article/how-to-make-a-tha=
nksgiving-charcuterie-board-everyone-will-be-thankful-for/" tabindex=3D"0" =
aria-label=3D"Thanksgiving charcuterie board" data-name=3D"Shop Now" data-m=
odule=3D"content engagement" data-position=3D"embedded links">Thanksgiving =
charcuterie board</a>.</p>
<h2>Do I have to buy one large turkey to feed a crowd?</h2>
<p>You don=E2=80=99t have to buy one large turkey to feed a crowd. Large tu=
rkeys are heavy and take a long time to cook, so you can easily divide the =
total number of pounds in two and buy two smaller birds. Cooking a small tu=
rkey (or a <a href=3D"https://www.tasteofhome.com/article/deconstructed-tur=
key/" tabindex=3D"0" aria-label=3D"deconstructed turkey" data-name=3D"Shop =
Now" data-module=3D"content engagement" data-position=3D"embedded links">de=
constructed turkey</a>!) is quicker, and the meat will cook more evenly.</p=
>
<p>When it comes to <a href=3D"https://www.tasteofhome.com/collection/tips-=
for-buying-perfect-turkey/" tabindex=3D"0" aria-label=3D"buying a turkey" d=
ata-name=3D"Shop Now" data-module=3D"content engagement" data-position=3D"e=
mbedded links">buying a turkey</a>, there=E2=80=99s a lot to consider. Here=
 are a few top-level tips to help you narrow things down:</p>
<ul>
<li><strong>Decide if you want to brine the turkey:</strong> If you plan to=
 <a href=3D"https://www.tasteofhome.com/article/how-to-brine-a-turkey/" tab=
index=3D"0" aria-label=3D"brine a turkey" data-name=3D"Shop Now" data-modul=
e=3D"content engagement" data-position=3D"embedded links">brine a turkey</a=
> at home, make sure the bird isn=E2=80=99t labeled as kosher, enhanced or =
self-basting. These labels indicate that the turkey has already been brined=
 or salted.</li>
<li><strong>Consider the turkey=E2=80=99s size:</strong> After calculating =
the turkey=E2=80=99s size based on the number of people you=E2=80=99re serv=
ing, determine <a href=3D"https://www.tasteofhome.com/article/roasting-pan-=
buying-guide/" tabindex=3D"0" aria-label=3D"what size roasting pan" data-na=
me=3D"Shop Now" data-module=3D"content engagement" data-position=3D"embedde=
d links">what size roasting pan</a> you=E2=80=99ll need. Then, double-check=
 that the bird will fit into the one you have at home.</li>
<li><strong>Look for a well-rounded bird:</strong> The breast should be esp=
ecially rounded, which indicates that the meat will be particularly juicy. =
Avoid turkeys with flat spots, a sign that the bird may have been thawed an=
d refrozen.</li>
</ul>
<h2>Can I make more white or dark meat?</h2>
<p>A whole turkey has a set amount of white meat (breasts and wings) and da=
rk meat (thighs and drumsticks), but you can easily cook turkey cuts on the=
 side to adjust the ratios. Pick up an extra turkey breast if your guests s=
trongly prefer white meat, or whip up some turkey legs to have more dark me=
at available. Try mixing and matching cooking methods to maximize your oven=
 space.</p><div class=3D"ad-container-wrapper dai-ad-wrapper glide-on-mobil=
e"><div id=3D"dai-content-2" class=3D"ad" data-ad-slot-name=3D"/article/con=
tent_2" data-ad-sizes=3D"" data-ad-targeting=3D"{&quot;pos&quot;:&quot;cont=
